opening_comment: Dragon Island. Marked as Morocco territory, whereas should be Western Sahara
closing_comment: Dragon Island is a tourist nickname. Here is an assumption that the coastline of the island resembles a dragon when viewed over it.  More credible is its derivation from 'kite surfing', (kite = dragon) the popular sport that, in the former times of campers and kite surfers until 2020, shaped the earlier image of the Dahkla Lagoone with countless colorful kite flyers.  the original name in Hassania 'Trouk' can also be found on French maps.  The Spanish 'Isla Herne', on the other hand, seems to go back to the first colonizer Hanno, 'the sailor' in 470 BC.  https://ceb.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isla_Herne  I am transferring this reference to the older reference to this island and closing this double naming

opening_comment: Hallo Ich würde gerne euch mitteilen, dass die Grenzziehung zwischen der Westsahara und Marokko einerseits und innerhalb der Westsahara andererseits falsch sind und völkerrechtswidrig sind. Die Westsahara ist von Marokko illegal besetzt. Eine UN-Mission ist vor Ort seit 1991. Sie wird MINURSO benannt und hat zur Aufgabe ein Selbstbestimmungsreferendum zu organisieren. Zur MINURSO und zum Konflikt findet ihr hier alle offiziellen Infomationen (https://minurso.unmissions.org). Die Westsahara ist zwar von der UNO nicht als unabhängiger Staat anerkannt. Es gilt jedoch als ein Nicht-Autonomes Territorium. Des Weiteren ist die Westsahara (offizieller Name Saharauische Arabische Republik Sara, SADR, bzw. Sahrawi Republic) ein Vollmitglied der Afrikanischen Union. Dies ist ebenfalls leicht überprüfbar auf der offiziellen Seite der Afrikanischen Union (https://au.int/en/member_states/countryprofiles2) Es ist deshalb sehr erstaunlich, dass ein Projekt wie OpenStreetMap eine illegale Besatzung durch falsche Grenzziehung unterstützt. Ich bitte euch höflichst die Grenzziehung richtigzustellen. Vielen Dank.
closing_comment: OpenStreetMap folgt hier der on-the-ground-Regel, in diesem Fall die Besetzung durch Marokko. Bitte entsprechend mit der OSMF-Policy dazu ( https://wiki.osmfoundation.org/w/images/d/d8/DisputedTerritoriesInformation.pdf) und gegebenenfalls https://wiki.openstreetmap.org/wiki/Disputed_territories#Africa auseinandersetzen.

opening_comment: Dear OpenStreetMap Community I would like to remark, that the borders between Western Sahara and Morocco and also inside Western Sahara are wrong. As you know Western Sahara was first a Spanish colony and was illegally occupied by Morocco in 1975. After a war of 16 years, the UN sent a mission. The mission is called MINURSO and you can find here all the official information to the international law conflict (https://minurso.unmissions.org). Moreover Western Sahra (official name: Sahrawi Arab Democratic Republic = SADR = Sahrawi Republic) is a full member of the African Union. You can proof this information easily by visiting the official site of the African Union (https://au.int/en/member_states/countryprofiles2). You don't have to follow any opinion of the conflict parties. You can just follow the international law, that says that Western Sahara is an Non-Autonomous territory. No organization and no international treaty ever recognized that Western Sahara was a part of Morocco. So pleas draw the right Western Sahara borders. Thank you very much!

opening_comment: Offering an indoor pool, Riad Magda & Spa is located in Marrakech. Free WiFi access is available.  Each room here will provide you with a TV and satellite channels. There is also a dining table. You can enjoy pool view from the room.  At Riad Magda & Spa you will find a spa and wellness centre and a restaurant. Other facilities offered at the property include meeting facilities and a shared lounge. An array of activities can be enjoyed on site or in the surroundings.  The riad is 600 m from Souk of the Medina, 700 m from Djemaa El Fna and 700 m from Marrakech Medina. Marrakech-Menara Airport is 4 km away.   Medina is a great choice for travellers interested in markets, street markets and shopping.  This is our guests' favourite part of Marrakech, according to independent reviews.  This property also has one of the best-rated locations in Marrakech! Guests are happier about it compared to other properties in the area.  Couples particularly like the location — they rated it 9.1 for a two-person trip.  This property is also rated for the best value in Marrakech! Guests are getting more for their money when compared to other properties in this city.

'I have been trying to find this place and it turned out to be extremely difficult, for that reason I would like to put it in OSM with its GPS location. The following description can be found in wikitravel:  Artisanal Association for Divorced Women. In the Fes el Jidid along the northern wall is an association for divorced women that sells high quality artisanal crafts. You will have to do some haggling, but the quality is good, the salesmen are very informative about technique, stories behind designs, and the various cultures represented in the artwork. Even if you don't want to buy anything, it is a nice representation of all of the things you might see in the market, and you can look at them without the hassle of a pushy salesman trying to help you look at what you see.   https://wikitravel.org/en/Fez' POI name: Le souk Artisanal de Fès POI types: shop-gift OSM data version: 2018-08-04T14:22:01Z  #mapsme

Wellcome to Casar Tamnougalt You are invited to come and spend with us a day in a unique berberic house in a picturesque village of Tamnougalt. You will have opportunity to live inside ruins of  berber village ruins from 16th century, in a home renovated  with love and compassion. You will have an opportunity to forget about all the stress of your every day life and enjoy in peacefull surroundings. There are just two rooms available, one with double bed and private bathroom for 2 persons and one with two double beds for 3 persons. In betwen them there is a nice terrace where you will have best breakfasts in a valley :)  How to find us: By bus go to Agdz and from there there is a local transport (shared taxi or just local car) which costs 5 Dh (0,5 eur). Our place is 7 km from Agdz, 2,5 km from the main road Agdz to Zagora.  Highlights/Best things to do: - getting lost among the ruins of the old village - enjoy your nights (and day) without any usuall noises, there is no traffic in an old village - walks or cycling along the valley is perfect - count houndreds of palms around you during the day and houndreds of stars above you at night - easy access to and from Agdz any time of a day - visit 170 old Caids Kasbah in Tamnougalt  and Glaoui Kasbah in Agdz - trekking the mountain Kissan above the village, we can organise full day trekking for you or overnight stay in the mountain  - on request we can organise for you 5 days trekking from Tamnougalt to Zagora ....and much more...
